| Website | Official website ![Edit this at Wikidata](image) |


</fragment>
<fragment>

*Forbes* named McMillon to its World's Most Powerful People list in 2014, 2015 and 2016 where he ranked No. 29, No. 32, No. 27 respectively.[31] ExecRank ranked McMillon No. 4 on its 2015 list of top CEOs for large companies.[32]


In December 2016, McMillon joined a business forum assembled by then president-elect Donald Trump to provide strategic and policy advice on economic issues.[33] In August 2017, McMillon wrote a rebuke of President Trump's response to the violent protests Charlottesville, Virginia in an email to all employees and on the internal company website that is viewable by the public. The statement said the President, "missed a critical opportunity to help bring our country together". A company spokesman said McMillon would continue to serve on a presidential advisory council on economic development.[34]


</fragment>
<fragment>

**Carl Douglas McMillon** (born October 17, 1966) is an American businessman, and the president and chief executive officer (CEO) of Walmart Inc.[1] He sits on the retailer's board of directors. Having first joined the company as a summer associate in high school, he became the company's fifth CEO in 2014. He previously led the company's Sam's Club division, from 2005 to 2009, and Walmart International, from 2009 to 2013.




## Early life[edit]


McMillon was born in Memphis, Tennessee,[2] and grew up in Jonesboro, Arkansas,[3] the eldest of three children born to Laura and Morris McMillon, a dentist who served in Vietnam.[4] His parents moved the family to Bentonville, Arkansas, the home of Walmart headquarters, when McMillon was 16.[4] A sports enthusiast, McMillon played point guard on the Bentonville High School basketball team.[4]



## Career[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>
7. ^ ***a*** ***b*** "Microsoft names former Sam's Club exec as new COO". Associated Press. August 4, 2005. Retrieved January 22, 2016. *McMillon joined Wal-Mart full time in early 1991 as a buyer trainee in sporting goods*.
8. **^** Jopson, Barney (November 25, 2013). "Doug McMillon's rise from the shop floor to the chief's chair". *Financial Times*. Retrieved January 22, 2016. *Six years later, in 1990, while studying for his MBA at the University of Tulsa, he rejoined Walmart at a store in Oklahoma, before moving to the head office in Bentonville, Arkansas, the following year*.
9. ^ ***a*** ***b*** ***c*** ***d*** Nisen, Max (November 27, 2013). "How Doug McMillon went to unloading trucks at Wal-Mart to its next CEO". *Business Insider*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.
10. **^** Citrano, Virginia (August 5, 2005). "Microsoft names Wal-Mart exec as COO". *Forbes*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.

</fragment>
<fragment>

McMillon has worked for Walmart throughout his career.[5] He took on his first role with the company as a teenager in 1984.[4][5] He later became a buyer, then moved into management roles before becoming CEO in 2014.[3][5]



### Early career[edit]


When he was a teenager, McMillon began his first job with Walmart as a summer associate. He worked during the summer[4] unloading trucks in a distribution center. After high school, McMillon attended University of Arkansas, where he graduated with a bachelor's degree in 1989.[6]


</fragment>
<fragment>
11. **^** Jopson, Barney (November 25, 2013). "Doug McMillon's rise from the shop floor to the chief's chair". *Financial Times*. Retrieved January 22, 2016. *In February 2009, Mr McMillon took over as president and chief executive of Walmart International, which has more than 6,300 stores and 823,000 staff in countries outside the US*.(subscription required)
12. ^ ***a*** ***b*** Wohl, Jessica; Martell, Allison (April 12, 2012). "Walmart International focusing on existing markets". *Reuters*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.
13. **^** Maylie, Devon (March 9, 2012). "Wal-Mart, Massmart merger approved in South Africa". *The Wall Street Journal*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.
14. **^** Rubin, Ben Fox (November 25, 2013). "Who is new Wal-Mart CEO Doug McMillon?". *The Wall Street Journal*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.

</fragment>
<fragment>

In September 2019, McMillion announced that the company would no longer sell ammunition used for handguns and military-style weapons. This policy update came as a result of the mass shooting which took place at a Walmart in El Paso, Texas in August 2019. McMillion's actions to create a dialogue and take actions around the issue, set a new precedent for how corporations and their leaders address these matters.[35]


  




## Personal life[edit]


McMillon lives with his wife, Shelley, in Bentonville, Arkansas.[19] They have two sons.[6] Doug McMillon is a born-again Christian.[36]



## References[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>

1. **^** "Walmart Executive Management". Retrieved February 3, 2021.
2. **^** "Wal-Mart CEO bio box". Associated Press. February 17, 2016. Retrieved February 17, 2016 – via The Gazette.
3. ^ ***a*** ***b*** ***c*** ***d*** Banjo, Shelly (November 25, 2013). "Wal-Mart taps veteran as new CEO". *The Wall Street Journal*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.
4. ^ ***a*** ***b*** ***c*** ***d*** ***e*** ***f*** ***g*** ***h*** ***i*** ***j*** ***k*** O'Keefe, Brian (June 4, 2015). "The man who's reinventing Walmart". *Fortune*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.
5. ^ ***a*** ***b*** ***c*** Barr, Alistair; McCoy, Kevin (November 26, 2013). "New Wal-Mart CEO compares retail success to basketball". *USA Today*. Retrieved January 22, 2016.
6. ^ ***a*** ***b*** ***c*** "Doug McMillon's competitive spirit works well at Walmart". *USA Today*. April 18, 2010. Retrieved January 22, 2016.

</fragment>
<fragment>

McMillon took over the company at a time of slowing growth and increased competition from rivals, such as Costco, Amazon.com, grocery store chains Kroger and Safeway, and discount chains of small stores like Family Dollar and Dollar General.[4] Within his first two years as chief executive, McMillon raised wages for hourly workers in the US, boosted the company's commitment to e-commerce and revamped Walmart's executive team. While increased spending on labor and Walmart's digital offerings lowered short-term profits, McMillon argued that the moves would lead to happier workers and better customer service,[18] as well as a better footing in a changing retail market.[19]


</fragment>
<fragment>

Walmart promoted McMillon to president and CEO of Sam's Club on August 4, 2005.[7][10] Under McMillon, the wholesaler emphasized marketing to small business customers.[3] Additionally, McMillon incorporated what *The Wall Street Journal* called "treasure hunt" items that are limited-selection expensive premium items, such as diamond necklaces and wine vacations, for sale next to cheap bulk goods in an attempt to compete with Costco.[3]



### Walmart International (2009–2013)[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>

During McMillon's tenure, Walmart International's sales growth outpaced Walmart US[14] and grew to 29 percent of total sales company-wide.[9] When McMillon first became head of the division, it comprised more than 3,300 stores in 14 countries.[15] When Walmart announced it would move him to head Walmart Stores, Inc. in late 2013, Walmart International operated 6,300 stores in 26 countries.[16][*failed verification*]



### CEO of Walmart, Inc. (2014–present)[edit]


![](image)McMillon speaks from the White House Rose Garden on the COVID-19 pandemic in April 2020
Walmart announced on November 25, 2013, that McMillon would immediately join the company's board of directors,[17] and would replace Mike Duke as Walmart CEO effective on February 1, 2014, becoming the company's fifth chief executive.[4]


</fragment>
<fragment>

The next year, as McMillon studied for a Master of Business Administration (MBA) from University of Tulsa, he called Walmart and told an executive he was interested in training to become a buyer when he completed his studies.[4] Soon thereafter, McMillon rejoined Walmart as an assistant manager at a Tulsa, Oklahoma, store.[4] After completing his MBA in 1991,[6] McMillon moved to Walmart's Bentonville headquarters to join the buyer-training program.[7][8] Originally in charge of buying fishing tackle,[4] he later took on various roles as a buyer and a merchandiser, dealing in food, clothes, crafts and furnishings.[9] He later worked as a general merchandise manager for Walmart's wholesale store division Sam's Club before taking an executive role at Walmart, overseeing toys, electronics, and sporting goods, among other areas.[9]



### Sam's Club (2005–2009)[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>

As CEO, McMillon sought to make a "positive difference" in other issues.[25] On March 31, 2015, McMillon issued a statement urging Arkansas Gov. Asa Hutchinson to veto the state's "religious freedom" bill.[28] McMillon said the bill "threatens to undermine the spirit of inclusion present throughout the state of Arkansas and does not reflect the values we proudly uphold".[28]


In June 2015, McMillon said the company would stop selling Confederate flag merchandise[21] following the shooting of nine black churchgoers in Charleston, South Carolina.[29] McMillon altered Walmart's gun sales. He told *CNNMoney* in an interview that Walmart's selection of firearms should be geared towards hunters and sports shooters.[30] In August 2015, the company ceased sales of military-style semiautomatic weapons.[30]


</fragment>
<fragment>

Walmart officials moved McMillon from his role at Sam's Club to lead Walmart's international division in February 2009,[11] replacing Mike Duke, who was promoted to CEO of Walmart Stores, Inc.[9] Under McMillon, Walmart International focused on improving in existing markets, such as Canada, China, United Kingdom and the Americas.[12] One area of particular importance to McMillon was integrating Walmart's "everyday low prices" model to these international markets.[12] Under McMillon, the international division acquired a majority stake in South Africa's Massmart Holdings Ltd. for US$2.4 billion.[4][13]

Here is some information about Andy Jassy:

- **Full Name**: Andrew R. Jassy
- **Date of Birth**: January 13, 1968
- **Education**: Harvard University (BA, MBA)
- **Known For**: Founding Amazon Web Services (AWS) and Amazon Music
- **Current Role**: President and CEO of Amazon
- **Previous Roles**: SVP and CEO of Amazon Web Services (2003-2021)
- **Spouse**: Elana Caplan (m. 1997)
- **Children**: 2

Andy Jassy is an American business executive who currently serves as the president and chief executive officer (CEO) of Amazon. He was appointed to this role by Jeff Bezos and the Amazon board during the fourth quarter of 2020. Prior to this, Jassy served as the SVP and later as the CEO of Amazon Web Services from 2003 to 2021.

Jassy joined Amazon as a marketing manager in 1997 with several other Harvard MBA colleagues. In 2003, he and Jeff Bezos came up with the idea to create the cloud computing platform that became known as Amazon Web Services, which launched in 2006. Jassy headed it and its team of 57 people.

In 2016, Jassy was named Person of the Year by the Financial Times. A month later, Jassy was promoted from senior vice president to chief executive officer of Amazon Web Services. That year Jassy earned $36.6 million.

For his work as chief executive officer of Amazon Web Services, Jassy earned a base compensation of $175,000 in 2020, plus a restricted stock unit award of 4,023 shares (a value of $12,104,844.93 as of July 26, 2020) of Amazon with vesting beginning in 2023. He also received a restricted stock unit award in April 2018 for 10,000 shares (a value of $30,089,100 as of July 26, 2020), which vest 37.5% in 2021, 12.5% in 2022, 37.5% in 2023, and 12.5% in 2024.

In January 2021, Bezos designated Jassy his official successor as CEO; with the transition occurring on July 5, 2021. As CEO of Amazon, Jassy received a ten year pay package totaling $212.7 million. The majority of the compensation package is in stock and vests over 10 years.

Jassy is the son of Margery and Everett L. Jassy of Scarsdale, New York. Jewish with Hungarian ancestry, his father was a senior partner in the corporate law firm Dewey Ballantine in New York City, and chairman of the firm's management committee. Jassy grew up in Scarsdale, and attended Scarsdale High School, where he played varsity soccer and tennis.

Jassy graduated cum laude from Harvard College in government, where he was advertising manager of The Harvard Crimson, before earning an MBA from Harvard Business School. In 1989, he wrote in The Crimson that the newspaper should continue to publish advertisements from Eastern Air Lines, despite an ongoing labor dispute there.

Jassy worked for five years after graduation before entering his MBA program as a project manager for a collectibles company, MBI, and then he and an MBI colleague started a company and closed it down.

In 1997, Jassy married Elana Rochelle Caplan, a fashion designer for Eddie Bauer and graduate of the Philadelphia College of Textiles and Science, at a Loews Hotel in Santa Monica, California. Their wedding was officiated by New York Rabbi James Brandt, a cousin of Elana. Both their fathers were senior partners in law firm Dewey Ballantine. Jassy and Caplan have two children.

They live in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Seattle in a 10,000-square-foot house bought in 2009 for $3.1 million. In October 2020, it was reported that Jassy had bought a $6.7 million 5,500-square-foot house in Santa Monica.

He is chairman of Rainier Prep, a charter school in Seattle.</s>
